	 * .queryAsync() method instead. That method will call .initQueryGetTokenAsync() and then
	 * .refreshQueryWithToken() in a loop until the query is complete (based on the arguments you
	 * specify), and then return the final response.
	 *
	 * @param {boolean} [executeAsync=false] - If set to true, the .executeAsync() method of
	 *  RESTMessageV2 will be used instead of the .execute() method. This may result in a longer
	 *  time between call and response, but may be preferable if the total number of requests is
	 *  very high, which could otherwise bog down instance performance.
	 * Note that this argument does not change whether this method itself is asynchronous; this
	 *  method does not accept a callback function. It only changes whether the RESTMessageV2
	 *  object is executed asynchronously within the instance. Server-side JavaScript code in
	 *  ServiceNow always executes "synchronously".
	 *
	 * If not specified, this argument defaults to the value of this.rest_async, which
	 *  initializes to false but can be set using the .setRESTAsync() method.
	 * Specifying the executeAsync argument here, overrides the behavior set by calling .setRESTAsync().
	 *
	 * See this link to ServiceNow's API documentation on .executeAsync():
	 * https://developer.servicenow.com/dev.do#!/reference/api/sandiego/server/sn_ws-namespace/c_RESTMessageV2API#r_RMV2-executeAsync
	 * @param {number} [maxWaitTime=5] - The maximum number of seconds to wait for the response.
	 * If this method is only used for initiating the query, it's recommended to leave this
	 *  unspecified and accept the default value of 5 seconds, or manually set it to <10 seconds.
	 * Never set this argument to a value greater than
	 * NOTE: This argument only does anything if using live data. As mentioned in the documentation,
	 *  this is accomplished by calling the .useLiveData() method.
	 * @param {number} [expectedCount=0] - The number of endpoints to eventually retrieve.
	 * If you're not sure how many endpoints you're expecting to respond, you can set this to 0
	 *  (or leave it unspecified and accept the default value of 0) and it will be ignored,
	 *  resulting in all endpoints matching any filters you've specified with the .addFilter()
	 *  method being retrieved.
	 * NOTE: This argument only does anything if using live data.
	 * @return {{data}|Object|Boolean} - Returns the response body from the Tanium API Gateway,
	 *  while also setting local properties like refresh cursor in order to prepare for refreshing
	 *  the query if the results are not complete in the response. You can tell if the results are
	 *  complete, because the data.endpoints.collectionInfo.success property will be set to true.
	 *  In the event that the query has expired (which typically happens after 5-10 minutes), the
	 *  data.endpoints.collectionInfo.active property will be set to false (in which case you'll
	 *  need to call this function again in order to begin a new query). The data.endpoints.edges
	 *  array may well be empty in the returned object. That is expected for queries that take
	 *  longer than a few seconds. In that case, you'll need to call
	 * .refreshQueryWithToken() and pass in the refresh token value from the
	 * data.endpoints.collectionInfo.startCursor node in order to get the results, once they're
	 * available.
	 *
	 * @example
	 * var percentResponded, queryResponse, refreshToken;
	 *
	 * var gqu = new x_taniu_tan_core.GatewayQueryUtil();
	 * var responseCount = 0;
	 * var maxLoops = 40;
	 * var currentLoop = 1;
	 * var minimumEndpoints = 1;
	 *
	 * gqu.useLiveData();
	 * gqu.addSensor('Computer Name');
	 * gqu.addSensor('Computer Serial Number');
	 *
	 * gqu.addFilter(
	 * 	'serialNumber',
	 * 	'CONTAINS',
	 * 	'some_serial_number'
	 * );
	 *
	 * queryResponse = gqu.initQueryGetTokenAsync();
	 * //Using + operator to return numeric representation of the respondedPercentage node.
	 * percentResponded = +queryResponse.data.endpoints.collectionInfo.respondedPercentage;
	 *
	 * //Halt after maxLoops, OR 90% response, OR responseCount >= minimumEndpoints
	 * while (currentLoop < maxLoops && percentResponded < 0.9 && responseCount < minimumEndpoints) {
