	 *  query will be retried before the result is returned. Each "poll" of the API using the
	 *  refresh token, the query will be retried until the query is complete (based on the other
	 *  arguments specified for this method, such as minimumResponsePercent or
	 *  minimumEndpointCount) or until the maxRetries limit is reached.
	 * If this value is set to 0 (or unspecified), it will be set to its default value which is
	 *  (180 (3 minutes) divided by the value of the maxWaitTimePerRequest argument). If
	 *  maxWaitTime is set to 3 (seconds), then maxRetries will be set to 180/3=60.
	 *
	 * @param {Boolean} [executeAsync=false] - If set to true, the .executeAsync() method of
	 *  RESTMessageV2 will be used instead of the .execute() method. This may result in a longer
	 *  time between call and response, but may be preferable if the total number of requests is
	 *  very high, which could otherwise bog down instance performance.
	 * Note that this argument does not change whether this method itself is asynchronous; this
	 *  method does not accept a callback function. It only changes whether the RESTMessageV2
	 *  object is executed asynchronously within the instance. Server-side JavaScript code in
	 *  ServiceNow always executes "synchronously".
	 * See this link to ServiceNow's API documentation on .executeAsync():
	 * https://developer.servicenow.com/dev.do#!/reference/api/sandiego/server/sn_ws-namespace/c_RESTMessageV2API#r_RMV2-executeAsync
	 *
	 * @param {Number} [expectedCount=0] - The number of endpoints to eventually retrieve.
	 * If you're not sure how many endpoints you're expecting to respond, you can set this to 0
	 *  (or leave it unspecified and accept the default value of 0) and it will be ignored,
	 *  resulting in all endpoints matching any filters you've specified with the .addFilter()
	 *  method being retrieved.
	 * NOTE: This argument only does anything if using live data.
	 * This is the number of endpoints that are expected to be returned by the query. This will
	 *  often be set to the same value as minimumEndpointCount, if used.
	 *
	 * @param {Number} [maxWaitTimePerRequest=5] - The maximum time (in seconds) to wait for a
	 *  response from the Tanium API Gateway *for each request*. Never set this to a value greater
	 *  than ~25. This is the maximum amount of time to wait for a response from the Tanium API
	 *  Gateway *for each request*. The .queryAsync() method will make multiple requests until
	 *  some condition is met (based on the arguments provided), so this value will be multiplied
	 *  by the number of requests made. A shorter maxWaitTimePerRequest argument may result in a
	 *  faster response. A value of 0 will result in the default value of 5 being used, just as
	 *  if the argument was not provided. The default value of 5 seconds is recommended, but any
	 *  value *between 3 and 10* is a good range to use. Any values >= 30 will be ignored, as
	 *  that would result in a potential timeout.
	 *
	 * @param {Boolean} [requireAvailableResults=false] - If set to false (or if unspecified),
	 *  the response will be returned even if it contains "[current result unavailable]" or
	 *  "[results currently unavailable]" for one or more sensors (as long as the other stopping
	 *  conditions are met).
	 * If set to true, the response will NOT be returned if it contains "[current result
	 *  unavailable]" or "[results currently unavailable]" for any of the requested sensors (unless
	 *  we've reached the maximum number of loops), meaning that it will continue attempting to
	 *  refresh the query until the stopping conditions are met, AND all sensors have a current
	 *  result available.
	 * This argument is only relevant if using live data. If using cached data, one should never
	 *  get a response without a "current" result.
	 * Setting this argument to true may result in a longer wait time for some sensors, as the
	 *  query will continue to be refreshed until all sensors have a current result available and
	 *  will ignore the other stopping conditions (except for the maximum refresh attempts) until
	 *  that happens.
	 *
	 * @returns {{data}} - The response body from the Tanium API Gateway, as a JavaScript object.
	 *
	 * @example
	 * var queryResponse;
	 *
	 * var gqu = new x_taniu_tan_core.GatewayQueryUtil();
	 * var minEndpoints = 1,
	 * 	minResponsePercent = 0,
	 * 	maxRetries = 15,
	 * 	executeAsync = true,
	 * 	expectedCount = 1,
	 * 	maxWaitTimePerRequest = 5;
	 *
	 * gqu.useLiveData(expectedCount);
	 *
	 * gqu.addSensor('Computer Name');
	 * gqu.addSensor('Computer Serial Number');
	 * gqu.addSensor('Endpoint ID');
	 *
	 * gqu.addFilter(
	 * 	'serialNumber',
	 * 	'CONTAINS',
	 * 	'some_serial_number'
	 * );
	 *
	 * queryResponse = gqu.queryAsync(
	 * 	minEndpoints,
	 * 	minResponsePercent,
	 * 	maxRetries,
	 * 	executeAsync,
	 * 	expectedCount,
	 * 	maxWaitTimePerRequest
